			<div class="post" id="post-63">
				<h2><a href="/courses/history120/spring07/mulatto-slaves-exceptionally-valuable-and-better-chances-of-escape.html" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Mulatto Slaves exceptionally valuable and better chances of escape.">Mulatto Slaves exceptionally valuable and better chances of escape.</a></h2>
				<small>February 6th, 2007 <!-- by hjathoul --></small>

				<div class="entry">
					<p><strong>    Mulatto slaves had very useful skills and were considered exceptionally valuable.</strong> The chances of escape as a Mulatto Slave where enhanced due to his or her color. As a Mulatto slave, chances of escape where increased since the skin color resembled that of Native Americans. As explained in many advertisements resembling Indians as appose to African American slaves made chances of escape much greater. As many Mulatto slaves disguised themselves as Indians wearing match coats and other Indian apparel, increasing their chances of escape and hiding out amongst Black Indians. Many where found hiding in forests and other wooded areas as they attempted to pass themselves off as Black Indians. It appears that the runaways had to be witty and cunning to portray themselves as freed slaves or a Black Indians.</p>
<p>These ads tell us a great deal about the courage and resilience these men and women had during these times of hardship. Some advertisements had warnings explaining how difficult it was to catch certain slaves. Many would escape again from the slave trackers or would not allow themselves to surrender or be taken alive. These advertisements help show us the mentality and courage of the runways. It took a strong willed person to run-a-way from is his or her master, as these slaves did not know what was waiting for them on the road to freedom. Many Mulatto slaves had acquired skills which were vital to plantations such as carpentry, farming, taming horses, and medicine. Some owners where willing to pay up to two hundred dollars for the return of their runaway slave. At that time that amount of money would equal big bucks today. It is clear that in having such skills as carpentry or horse taming a lot of these slaves could be earning good money as freed slaves.</p>
<p>In most advertisements it seems as if the slave owners are showcasing the talents of the runaway slaves. The way certain texts are written makes it appear as if the slaves made a bad choice and just needed to find there way back to the plantation. They disguise the fact that a human is owned by another human. The Mulatto slaves had a better chance of escape due to their mixed color and their ability to take advantage of that. This history lesson shows us that when people are treated unjustly, they will find ways to rise above it.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/saxon/servlet/SaxonServlet?source=/vcdh/xml_docs/slavery/ads/md1752.xml&amp;style=/vcdh/xml_docs/slavery/ads/display_ad.xsl&amp;ad=m1752050001">Green</a>     <a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/saxon/servlet/SaxonServlet?source=/vcdh/xml_docs/slavery/ads/md1779.xml&amp;style=/vcdh/xml_docs/slavery/ads/display_ad.xsl&amp;ad=m1779060005">Goddard</a>     <a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/saxon/servlet/SaxonServlet?source=/vcdh/xml_docs/slavery/ads/md1780.xml&amp;style=/vcdh/xml_docs/slavery/ads/display_ad.xsl&amp;ad=m1780120004">Green2</a></p>
				</div>

				<p class="postmetadata">Posted in <a href="/courses/history120/spring07/category/assignments" title="View all posts in Assignments" rel="category tag">Assignments</a>,  <a href="/courses/history120/spring07/category/assignment-1" title="View all posts in Assignment #1" rel="category tag">Assignment #1</a> |   <a href="/courses/history120/spring07/mulatto-slaves-exceptionally-valuable-and-better-chances-of-escape.html#comments" title="Comment on Mulatto Slaves exceptionally valuable and better chances of escape.">29 Comments &#187;</a></p>
			</div>

		
			<div class="post" id="post-62">
				<h2><a href="/courses/history120/spring07/convicts-or-free-people.html" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Convicts or Free People">Convicts or Free People</a></h2>
				<small>February 6th, 2007 <!-- by cpatel --></small>

				<div class="entry">
					<p>After looking at different advertisement for runaway slaves I learned something different about slaves.  <strong>In each article the slaves were called English servant man or woman rather than slaves or Negro’s and the owners knew them really well physically and their personality.  </strong>Another point the advertisements make is that the slaves use different methods to hide themselves so they can’t be found for example in the article on October 24<sup>th</sup> 1745 <a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/gos/search/relatedAd.php?adFile=sg45.xml&amp;adId=v1745101395">James Gibson</a> who ran away lied to everyone who he came across and as noted by the owner as a cunning fellow.  Another example of this was printed on November 11<sup>th</sup> 1747 where <a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/gos/search/relatedAd.php?adFile=md1747.xml&amp;adId=m1747110004">Margaret Barnes</a> who ran away and claims to everyone that she could predict fortunes for others.  The articles that I read did not state what skills the servants possessed and the reason behind that is that the owners did not what to alert others with the skills their servant’s possessed. This might be a problem in the process of getting them back since the servants will do what they do best in to earn a living while away from their masters.<br />
In the last article that I read was the one where <a href="http://www.vcdh.virginia.edu/gos/search/relatedAd.php?adFile=sg45.xml&amp;adId=v1745041377">John Owl</a> ran away from his master and the interesting part on the advertisement was that he ran away last on February 14<sup>th</sup>.  This tells a lot about Mr. Owl who ran away more than once but was found and returned in the previous incidents.  All the articles were very through with the different clothing that they wore right before fleeing off and also different kinds of scars or any other physical appearance that would identify them.  The advertisements did a lot of great thing describing the servants.<br />
Slaves are all kept against their will as said in the wikipedia article of slavery “Slaves are people who are held against their will since either their capture, their purchase, or their birth, and are deprived of their individual freedom for the purpose of exploitation of their labour and in some cases their sexual abuse.” [1]  This tells us that they never had it easy with their masters so in return they ran away and never returned and if found they would try to find another way to escape  such as Mr. Owl who ran away a couple of times.<br />
All these advertisments shows us how much the owners miss their servants because of the output they gave to the owners such as farming, shoe maker and many more other things.  Inaddition the advertisments also pointed out that they were not called slaves but instead called servant man or woman and the amount of information that they owners knew about them.</p>
<p>[1] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slavery</p>
				</div>

				<p class="postmetadata">Posted in <a href="/courses/history120/spring07/category/assignments" title="View all posts in Assignments" rel="category tag">Assignments</a>,  <a href="/courses/history120/spring07/category/assignment-1" title="View all posts in Assignment #1" rel="category tag">Assignment #1</a> |   <a href="/courses/history120/spring07/convicts-or-free-people.html#comments" title="Comment on Convicts or Free People">28 Comments &#187;</a></p>
			</div>

		
